               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1068" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1068" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1068" type="surname" value="SOLOMON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1068" type="given" value="ABRAHAM"></interp>ABRAHAM SOLOMON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">through an interpreter.</hi>) The prisoner was in my ✗ vice. On the 18th of March he took out fifteen pairs of shoes—he said he sold them to Mr. Jones—he did not give me the money—he made me enter them✗ in the book to Mr. Jones, fifteen pairs of shoes, at 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-dozen, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he had leave to sell shoes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you been in Eng<lb></lb>land? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Eighteen months—I have been in business about twelve months in Goulston-square, Whitechapel—I am a native of France—I know Ments—I went honourably, there and came away honourably—my wife did not come to this country with me—she lived in France till I had lived here about eight months, when I wrote to her to come—I did not leave her there in any business—I gave up business when I left—I know nothing about her being put into prison for concealing my effects—I was oncei n partnership with a man named Altham—I have not been to Mr. Hart, the beadle of the Great Synagogue, and asked him for 9<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to keep away from this prosecution—Mr. Hart has been to my house and inquired what the prisoner had dose, and I told him all the circumstances about it—I can swear I did not ask for 9<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. to keep away from this prosecution—I did not go to the Rev. Dr. Alder and ask him for money—he sent his servant for me; I went, and heard what he wanted of me—the prisoner told me he had been a wholesale shoe<lb></lb>maker on his own account—I did not agree with him that he was to bring me his connexion—he was to find a connexion—we were not to divide the profits—he had 25<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week—I have his receipts for that—he was not to receive 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a-week and one quarter of the profits—he was not to have any✗ portion of the profits—he has complained to me about the way in which I keep my books.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470510-name-1069" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1069" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1069" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470510-name-1069" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES JONES</persName>
                  </hi>. I sometimes purchase things of the prisoner—I did not purchase any shoes of him on the 18th of March.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You have purchased things of the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes Abel Solomon was known to me, through the prisoner—the prisoner was the person I dealt with, and I paid him on delivery.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
